TITLE: Creating Non-Root User with SSH Key Access in Bash
DESCRIPTION: This snippet demonstrates how to create a non-root user on a Unix-like system using Bash commands. It includes steps to generate an SSH key, add a user without a password, and enable key-based SSH login. Dependencies: Requires sudo privileges and SSH setup on the server. Main parameters are <username> and <your ssh private key>.
SOURCE: https://github.com/casper-network/docs-redux/blob/dev/versioned_docs/version-1.5.X/operators/setup/non-root-user.md#2025-04-22_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: Bash
CODE:
```
sudo adduser <username> --disabled-password
```

LANGUAGE: Bash
CODE:
```
sudo su - <username>
mkdir .ssh
chmod 700 .ssh
touch .ssh/authorized_keys
```

LANGUAGE: Bash
CODE:
```
exit
```

LANGUAGE: Bash
CODE:
```
sudo visudo
```

LANGUAGE: Bash
CODE:
```
# User privilege specification
root    ALL=(ALL:ALL) ALL
<username>  ALL=(ALL:ALL) NOPASSWD:ALL
```

LANGUAGE: Bash
CODE:
```
ssh -i <your ssh private key> <username>@<server ip>
```

LANGUAGE: Bash
CODE:
```
ssh -i ~/.ssh/id_rsa casper@10.21.10.200
```

